fields.name: Bakor Nature Camp
fields.description: Bakor is a beautiful village situated in Mahisagar District of Gujarat. The campsite is located close to Rajasthan Border. In monsoon, Bakor is full of green grass, shrubs, bushes and green tall trees. Bakor Natural Camp is a unique eco-tourism destination located in the lush green forest region of Gujarat, India. It is a perfect retreat for nature lovers and adventure enthusiasts seeking a tranquil and serene getaway from the hustle and bustle of city life.  The campsite is situated in the midst of a dense forest and offers a breathtaking view of the surrounding landscape. The area is rich in flora and fauna, with a variety of rare and exotic species that can be spotted during treks and hikes in the forest.  The Bakor Natural Camp is designed to provide a rustic and authentic experience of living in the forest. The campsite features comfortable tents that are equipped with basic amenities such as beds, blankets, and pillows. There are no attached bathrooms in the tents,

fields.name: Rann Utsav
fields.description: Immerse in the more vibrant, more delightful and more interesting Rann Utsav-The Tent City experience. Spend a luxurious holiday glamping in the rich cultural city, the adventure activities, Full and Dark Moon experiences and incredible sights to visit. Ranotsav, also known as the Rann Utsav, is a cultural festival that takes place annually in the Rann of Kutch region in the Indian state of Gujarat. This festival is celebrated in the months of December to February every year and attracts thousands of tourists from all over the world.  The Rann of Kutch is a vast salt desert located in the western part of India. This region is known for its unique landscape, rich culture, and vibrant traditions. The Ranotsav festival is a celebration of all of these elements and is a great way to experience the essence of Gujarat.  The festival is a colorful affair, with traditional dances, music, and art performances.

fields.name: Somnath First Jyotirlinga
fields.description:
Somnath is a beautiful city in Gujarat that radiates positivity all the time. Somnath posses the most famous Somnath temple which is a place of worship for numerous pilgrims all over the country.
Jyotirlingas are sacred shrines of Lord Shiva; it is believed that Lord Shiva himself visited these places and hence they have a special place in the hearts of devotees. There are 12 of them in India.

Jyotirlinga means column or pillar of light. The stambha symbol represents that there is no beginning or end.
When Lord Brahma and Lord Vishnu had an argument about who was the supreme god, Lord Shiva appeared as a column of light and asked each one to find the ends. Neither could do it. It is believed that the places where these columns of light fell is where the jyotirlingas are located.

The most sacred of the 12 jyotirlingas in India is the Somnath Jyotirlinga.
